snippet.title: amber heard partners with sams to launch pss programs for syrian refugee women in lebanon
snippet.description:
this past february, actress & activist amber heard joined sams on a women‚Äôs health mission to lebanon, targeting syrian refugee women who have limited or no access to care. during her trip, she visited a number of informal settlements in the beka‚Äôa valley where sams has provided and continues to provide medical care, from primary health care care to psychosocial support services.
one of the informal settlements she visited was  al-omaria, the only camp specifically designated for widows and their children in the beka‚Äôa valley. there are 25 widows and their 60 children residing in this settlement. all the widows are registered with the unhcr, and 80% receive a monthly stipend of $27 for living costs. once a widow‚Äôs son reaches the age of 13, the widow is given the choice to either force her son to leave the settlement on his own, or have the whole family depart from the settlement.
as a result of the trauma and loss experienced, these widows are in dire need of psychosocial support to help them cope with their emotional fatigue. amber has partnered with sams on a new crowdrise campaign to support these women and children.
please join our campaign today: www.crowdrise/amberheardlebanon

snippet.localized.title: Amber Heard Partners with SAMS to Launch PSS Programs for Syrian Refugee Women in Lebanon
snippet.localized.description:
This past February, actress & activist Amber Heard joined SAMS on a women‚Äôs health mission to Lebanon, targeting Syrian refugee women who have limited or no access to care. During her trip, she visited a number of informal settlements in the Beka‚Äôa Valley where SAMS has provided and continues to provide medical care, from primary health care care to psychosocial support services.
One of the informal settlements she visited was  Al-Omaria, the only camp specifically designated for widows and their children in the Beka‚Äôa Valley. There are 25 widows and their 60 children residing in this settlement. All the widows are registered with the UNHCR, and 80% receive a monthly stipend of $27 for living costs. Once a widow‚Äôs son reaches the age of 13, the widow is given the choice to either force her son to leave the settlement on his own, or have the whole family depart from the settlement.
As a result of the trauma and loss experienced, these widows are in dire need of psychosocial support to help them cope with their emotional fatigue. Amber has partnered with SAMS on a new CrowdRise campaign to support these women and children.
Please join our campaign today: www.crowdrise/amberheardlebanon

snippet.title: james marsden and amber heard will star in 'the stand,' a limited series based on the stephen king n
snippet.description:
(2 aug 2019) james marsden, amber heard to star in 'the stand' based on stephen king novel
james marsden and amber heard will star in ``the stand,'' a limited series based on the stephen king novel.
 cbs all access said thursday (01aug2019) that king will write the final chapter of the drama, a coda not in his book about a plague-devastated world.
marsden will play stu, a factory worker facing an extraordinary situation. heard's character is nadine, who follows an evil being with supernatural powers.
odessa young and henry zaga also will be part of the cast, the streaming service said.
``the stand'' was adapted for a 1994 miniseries, which was written by king and included gary sinise and ruby dee in the cast.
the premiere date and other stars of cbs all access' ``the stand'' have yet to be announced.

snippet.localized.description:
(2 Aug 2019) JAMES MARSDEN, AMBER HEARD TO STAR IN 'THE STAND' BASED ON STEPHEN KING NOVEL
James Marsden and Amber Heard will star in ``The Stand,'' a limited series based on the Stephen King novel.
 CBS All Access said Thursday (01AUG2019) that King will write the final chapter of the drama, a coda not in his book about a plague-devastated world.
Marsden will play Stu, a factory worker facing an extraordinary situation. Heard's character is Nadine, who follows an evil being with supernatural powers.
Odessa Young and Henry Zaga also will be part of the cast, the streaming service said.
``The Stand'' was adapted for a 1994 miniseries, which was written by King and included Gary Sinise and Ruby Dee in the cast.
The premiere date and other stars of CBS All Access' ``The Stand'' have yet to be announced.

snippet.title: yayo | passion play, london fields, american hustle
snippet.description:
i wanted to do something revolving around megan fox's character in passion play (lily) and nicola and guy's dynamic in london fields. they're pretty similar. the video is about disenfranchised women feeling trapped by poverty and abuse, escaping through rushing into relationships in the hopes of being saved, and using hypersexuality as a way of coping with their past/trying to escape their present. to quote the seven husbands of evelyn hugo, "it just goes to show that if you tell a woman her only skill is to be desirable, she will believe you."

disclaimer: i made this well before all the amber heard stuff. i still don't know what the deal with that was and i don't want to. men and self-hating women didn't believe her when she came forward about jd. i don't want to validate their belief that all survivors are liars because jd, the abuser, claimed he was abused when his career was effectively over. as i said, i don't know much about the case but i know one of his employee's corroborated amber's story in court. there was sufficient enough evidence that amber won her case. she donated the money as she said she would.

clips: american hustle, london fields, passion play, baby (netflix), the royals, daughter's "numbers" music video

also featuring: irving rosenfeld (christian bale), nate poole (mickey rourke), happy shannon (bill murray), sam adamo (rhys ifans), guy clinch (theo james), samson young (billy bob thornton), keith talent (jim sturgess)

snippet.title: michael takes action after having proof regarding the dna test | nang ngumiti ang langit recap
snippet.description:
nang ngumiti ang langit:  week 23 recap - part 1
nang ngumiti ang langit: august 26-28 episode (with english subtitles)

fed up with his father's harsh remarks toward james (enzo pineda), michael (rk bagatsing) gives elizabeth's (tetchie agbayani) final letter to david (dante rivero). meanwhile, atty. sandejas (nina ricci alagao) informs divina (pilar pilapil) that grace (shaina magdayao) is the witness they are looking for. because of this, divina comes up with a wicked plan against the nurse. grace, on the other hand, tells ruth what she knows about lloyd (carlos morales). later, michael discovers the person who tampered with his paternity test with amber (krystal mejes).

katrina (cristine reyes) remains adamant on staying at michael's (rk bagatsing) home. she orders her men to get rid of grace (shaina magdayao) while grace tries to find stronger evidence of the tampered paternity test. sensing katrina's devious intentions, ruth (matet de leon) urges michael to protect grace. barbie (moi bien), meanwhile, discovers shocking information on the attack she suffered at her boss' old house. elsewhere, benjie (keempee de leon) finds a way to distract the children from the chaos at their home.

enraged over michael's (rk bagatsing)'s decision, katrina (cristine reyes) forces her daughters to pack their stuff. despite britney's (heart ramos) pleas, she drags her daughters along as she leaves michael's home for good. amber (krystal mejes), on the other hand, is outraged upon confirming katrina's lie. meanwhile, divina (pilar pilapil) hatches up a plan that will put david (dante rivero) behind bars. later, amber lashes out on britney for wishing to return to mikmik's (sophia reola) side.

She orders her men to get rid of Grace (Shaina Magdayao) while Grace tries to find stronger evidence of the tampered paternity test. Sensing Katrina's devious intentions, Ruth (Matet de Leon) urges Michael to protect Grace. Barbie (Moi Bien), meanwhile, discovers shocking information on the attack she suffered at her boss' old house. Elsewhere, Benjie (Keempee de Leon) finds a way to distract the children from the chaos at their home.

Enraged over Michael's (RK Bagatsing)'s decision, Katrina (Cristine Reyes) forces her daughters to pack their stuff. Despite Britney's (Heart Ramos) pleas, she drags her daughters along as she leaves Michael's home for good. Amber (Krystal Mejes), on the other hand, is outraged upon confirming Katrina's lie. Meanwhile, Divina (Pilar Pilapil) hatches up a plan that will put David (Dante Rivero) behind bars. Later, Amber lashes out on Britney for wishing to return to Mikmik's (Sophia Reola) side.

snippet.title: domestic abuse of amber heard - ex-staff partner of johnny depp (jane doe)
snippet.description:
domestic abuse of amber heard according to ex-johnny depp staff's partner. she said her partner was there to see the marriage in 2014/2015 up to a 2017 nda.
- jane doe says amber heard was kicked, hit, and was crying after fights with depp. she said her partner and other staff checked on her. the full 140 or so screenshots are at: https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1gy4pw8yopvsy3t2vzs_zqp_9_-fmywie?usp=sharing

to prevent domestic abuse - get involved! believe early, let them escape early. we created a petition to support amber heard: https://www.change.org/p/amber-heard-supporters-we-support-amber-heard-in-aquaman-2

"mo*ster" as staff called depp was used also by this jane doe and said 7 people were watching these tweets. they were even called to stop talking to us and to not support either side. she mentioned amber was kicked in the uk, island, and other places.

divided, she said she knew depp and his staff, but not amber heard.

- the jane doe mentioned emails that she couldn't share now after the march 29 & april 1 screenshots, script writers, inability of amber to audition, the jane doe going to oscar/emmy parties, celebrities hiding bruises while going to events as common, and more...

amber heard is a crime victim which should also be a protected class.

- slideshow of the tweets and messages with music.

background: 
i did not know anything about heard or depp prior to depp's march 2019 lawsuit for defamation. i started to learn and defend amber in this situation, then this jane doe was looking on twitter, and she decided to support amber heard.

she did not want screenshots, however, if someone is going to talk about domestic abuse and know it occurred, then i think it should be said and exposed. los angeles is very behind and unsafe about equal rights, women's rights, worker's rights (e.g. pay, networking, ndas), and more. it can cause a chain reaction.

this slideshow shows jane doe clearly knew more than any ah fan did. jane doe said there was fighting from both sides, but they clearly saw depp as the oppressor, amber as the victim/survivor, and people are taking situations out of context. several people lost jobs when he threatened trump.

make your own decision from these tweets and messages, but i think amber heard is the victim here. also, a person can fall down or get hit, and have no bruises, especially if with young skin. they can take time to show up. to make a victim require bruises is going too far. coercive control goes beyond this to emotional, financial, and legal. it shouldn't have to get physical.

*also, limo drivers may have negative stories on many stars on the screen. one, e.g., i recently heard from one of their relatives in sedona that depp is mean...

the "jane doe" repeatedly changed their usernames on twitter, but it's the same person.

duty to rescue and duty to care:
(honestly, when i got these messages in april, i didn't really sleep and i got up early and screenshotted them before they temporarily deactivated their account (they would deactivate, lock, and change usernames). i am a defender because i believe in ‚Äúduty to rescue‚Äù law which makes me feel liable if i see something wrong or unethical. i didn't/do not want to be socially responsible if it was not shown, and i didn't believe investigating because of harmful imposter pis taking it out of context and threatening humanitarian work and lives).

if someone is in a harmful relationship, they should leave that relationship. the best way is to walk away. "better off without you anyway." to really prevent, though: people have to do something with duty to rescue and duty to care. women are often told that they should forget their violence, that it's not believed, and it's not stopped early. see something, do something. we have over 90,000 views of "men help woman being beaten by husband in parking lot": https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qyd0aougm2q

we also got the database fixed for the article on amber's friend calling 911 for her. it was not showing up: http://refinery29.com/en-us/2016/06/113149/domestic-violence-911-call-famous-friend.

stop ndas hiding discrimination, crime, and abuse:
harvey weinstein used ndas and networking to silence his victims. depp put his staff and amber heard onto ndas. ndas should be about intellectual property, not relationships. it's silencing victims and creates victim blaming. a 2017 law nearly came into effect to stop ndas. 
i am glad the aclu and times up are helping amber heard.

i stand with melissa benoist (supergirl - cw/wb):
not long after editing and adding dc/wb to emails for the petition, melissa benoist came out about domestic abuse. we cannot prove the timing, but also "i stand with melissa." we stand with you, amber. https://www.change.org/p/amber-heard-supporters-we-support-amber-heard-in-aquaman-2

in 2018, james wan‚Äôs aquaman became a remarkably surprising smash hit. nobody really knew what to expect from it for multiple reasons, given that it was following the disappointing release of justice league; centered on a character who had never had his own live-action solo movie. naturally, the excitement that the project generated immediately led warner bros. to solidify a future for the franchise, and within a few weeks of aquaman‚Äôs release we learned about their plans to develop an aquaman 2.

it‚Äôs typical for hollywood studios to try and produce sequels as quickly as they possibly can. after all, they don‚Äôt want to let the heat of a burgeoning franchise die down, and the more time that passes means there‚Äôs more opportunities for audiences to be distracted by other big properties. that being said, aquaman 2 is taking an extra minute to find its way to theaters, as warner bros. has announced that the blockbuster follow-up is currently scheduled to be released on december 22, 2022.

so, why is aquaman 2 coming out about four years after its predecessor? for starters, producer peter safran has noted that the filmmakers behind the movie don‚Äôt feel the need to rush the project, believing that giving the sequel the most development time possible will ultimately be beneficial for the final product. but that‚Äôs not the only reason. not only is the film going to need some legitimate time to actually get made from a logistics standpoint (it‚Äôs not super easy creating those underwater environments), but there are also many other dc extended universe titles in the works that the studio is developing between now and december 2022.

snippet.title: johnny depp sues amber heard for defamation seeking $50 million!
snippet.description:
the toxic divorce back-and-forth between hollywood stars johnny depp and amber heard continues with the latest legal front shifting to depp's reported lawsuit against his ex, seeking $50 million for allegedly defaming him with "hoax" allegations of domestic abuse.

the blast, deadline and people reported depp filed the suit against heard over an opinion column she published, but didn't say when or where or in what court the suit was filed. 

depp's lawyer, adam waldman of washington d.c., did not respond to emails from usa today. but he and depp, 55, have long vigorously denied allegations depp ever abused heard, asserting that she faked the abuse claims in 2016 and that depp was the real victim in their dispute.

"first she abused him physically, then she abused his reputation," waldman told usa today in december. 

heard's lawyer, eric george of los angeles, told usa today he had not yet seen the lawsuit, only the media reports about it. but he issued a statement condemning it as "frivolous" and vowed it would not stop heard from speaking out further about domestic violence. 

‚Äúthis frivolous action is just the latest of johnny depp‚Äôs repeated efforts to silence amber heard," george said in a statement emailed to usa today. "she will not be silenced.

"mr. depp‚Äôs actions prove he is unable to accept the truth of his ongoing abusive behavior.  but while he appears hell-bent on achieving self destruction, we will prevail in defeating this groundless lawsuit and ending the continued vile harassment of my client by mr. depp and his legal team.‚Äù

in december, heard, 32, who had accused depp of beating her before their 2016 divorce was finalized, wrote an opinion column in the washington post lamenting the consequences she paid for speaking out about the need to curb domestic violence.
two years ago, she wrote, "i became a public figure representing domestic abuse, and i felt the full force of our culture‚Äôs wrath for women who speak out."

she never mentioned the "pirates of the caribbean" star by name but it was clear who and what she was talking about, according to depp's lawsuit. her column "depends on the central premise that ms. heard was a domestic abuse victim and that mr. depp perpetrated domestic violence against her.‚Äù

these are ‚Äúfalse" allegations, depp's lawsuit argues, ‚Äúpart of an elaborate hoax to generate positive publicity‚Äù for heard to advance her career. ‚Äúms. heard is not a victim of domestic abuse; she is a perpetrator,‚Äù the suit says.

the depp-heard divorce, after less than two years of marriage, was one of hollywood's most toxic in 2016, an ugly affair featuring allegations of physical abuse, restraining orders, media-mobbed court hearings, leaked texts and cellphone pictures of facial bruises, plus dueling lawyers and publicists.

heard claimed the los angeles police went to their downtown loft the night of an alleged beating and documented the abuse. but the cops instead told reporters they found no evidence of a crime when they arrived.

after a summer of sniping, heard withdrew her allegations that depp abused her and the two settled their divorce out of court in august 2016. they issued a joint statement to the media.
"our relationship was intensely passionate and at times volatile, but always bound by love," the statement said. "neither party has made false accusations for financial gain. there was never any intent of physical or emotional harm. amber wishes the best for johnny in the future."

snippet.localized.title: Johnny Depp sues Amber Heard for defamation seeking $50 million!
snippet.localized.description:
The toxic divorce back-and-forth between Hollywood stars Johnny Depp and Amber Heard continues with the latest legal front shifting to Depp's reported lawsuit against his ex, seeking $50 million for allegedly defaming him with "hoax" allegations of domestic abuse.

The Blast, Deadline and People reported Depp filed the suit against Heard over an opinion column she published, but didn't say when or where or in what court the suit was filed. 

Depp's lawyer, Adam Waldman of Washington D.C., did not respond to emails from USA TODAY. But he and Depp, 55, have long vigorously denied allegations Depp ever abused Heard, asserting that she faked the abuse claims in 2016 and that Depp was the real victim in their dispute.

"First she abused him physically, then she abused his reputation," Waldman told USA TODAY in December. 

Heard's lawyer, Eric George of Los Angeles, told USA TODAY he had not yet seen the lawsuit, only the media reports about it. But he issued a statement condemning it as "frivolous" and vowed it would not stop Heard from speaking out further about domestic violence. 

‚ÄúThis frivolous action is just the latest of Johnny Depp‚Äôs repeated efforts to silence Amber Heard," George said in a statement emailed to USA TODAY. "She will not be silenced.

"Mr. Depp‚Äôs actions prove he is unable to accept the truth of his ongoing abusive behavior.  But while he appears hell-bent on achieving self destruction, we will prevail in defeating this groundless lawsuit and ending the continued vile harassment of my client by Mr. Depp and his legal team.‚Äù

In December, Heard, 32, who had accused Depp of beating her before their 2016 divorce was finalized, wrote an opinion column in the Washington Post lamenting the consequences she paid for speaking out about the need to curb domestic violence.
Two years ago, she wrote, "I became a public figure representing domestic abuse, and I felt the full force of our culture‚Äôs wrath for women who speak out."

She never mentioned the "Pirates of the Caribbean" star by name but it was clear who and what she was talking about, according to Depp's lawsuit. Her column "depends on the central premise that Ms. Heard was a domestic abuse victim and that Mr. Depp perpetrated domestic violence against her.‚Äù

These are ‚Äúfalse" allegations, Depp's lawsuit argues, ‚Äúpart of an elaborate hoax to generate positive publicity‚Äù for Heard to advance her career. ‚ÄúMs. Heard is not a victim of domestic abuse; she is a perpetrator,‚Äù the suit says.

The Depp-Heard divorce, after less than two years of marriage, was one of Hollywood's most toxic in 2016, an ugly affair featuring allegations of physical abuse, restraining orders, media-mobbed court hearings, leaked texts and cellphone pictures of facial bruises, plus dueling lawyers and publicists.

Heard claimed the Los Angeles police went to their downtown loft the night of an alleged beating and documented the abuse. But the cops instead told reporters they found no evidence of a crime when they arrived.

After a summer of sniping, Heard withdrew her allegations that Depp abused her and the two settled their divorce out of court in August 2016. They issued a joint statement to the media.
"Our relationship was intensely passionate and at times volatile, but always bound by love," the statement said. "Neither party has made false accusations for financial gain. There was never any intent of physical or emotional harm. Amber wishes the best for Johnny in the future."

Heard eventually donated her share of the divorce settlement, about $7 million, to a charity focused on fighting domestic abuse of women. In addition to her thriving acting career ("Aquaman"), she is now an ambassador on women‚Äôs rights for the American Civil Liberties Union.

Depp has been enmeshed in several lawsuits in recent years, including one against his former managers and another against his former attorneys. He's also pursuing a libel case against The Sun tabloid in London, where libel suits are easier for plaintiffs to win, for calling him a "wife-beater" based on Heard's allegations.

snippet.title: tea & autism - what's the connection?
snippet.description:
a new study has shown that our amber gaba oolong may help people with autism spectrum condition (asc). we meet dr anna joyce who is one of the researchers of the study to discuss the study and what this might mean for future research.

‚≠êÔ∏è try amber gaba oolong: https://meileaf.com/p/tea-agac
üëâ read the study: https://doi.org/10.1080/1028415x.2019.1588486

(if anyone wants to read the full study without paying then i can send on an individual basis but cannot share publicly - please email sales-support@meileaf.com requesting a copy of the study)

gaba (gamma-amino butyric acid) is a neurotransmitter which helps to balance out hyperreactivity in the brain and has been implicated in the control of conditions such as anxiety and sleep disorders. gabaergic neurons are thought to have a crucial role in emotional processing, sensory discrimination and this may impact motor skills.

features of autism tend to be over-excitability of the senses (visual, tactile and auditory) which can affect sensorimotor skills (balance, dexterity, stress, sleep and emotional processing. since gaba is the main neurotransmitter for reducing over-excitability, it stands to reason to figure out how gaba is involved in asc (autism spectrum condition).

it turns out that people with autism have much lower gaba levels in their brains than typical brains. this is due to structural and functional differences in the parts of the brain which produce gaba as well as a likelihood that the conversion process of glutamate to gaba is impaired in people with asc. therefore, the sensory overloading in people with autism is likely to be related to this reduced gaba and supplementing with gaba may be useful.

snippet.localized.title: TEA & AUTISM - What's the connection?
snippet.localized.description:
A new study has shown that our Amber GABA Oolong may help people with Autism Spectrum Condition (ASC). We meet Dr Anna Joyce who is one of the researchers of the study to discuss the study and what this might mean for future research.

‚≠êÔ∏è TRY AMBER GABA OOLONG: https://meileaf.com/p/tea-agac
üëâ READ THE STUDY: https://doi.org/10.1080/1028415X.2019.1588486

(if anyone wants to read the full study without paying then I can send on an individual basis but cannot share publicly - please email sales-support@meileaf.com requesting a copy of the study)

GABA (gamma-amino butyric acid) is a neurotransmitter which helps to balance out hyperreactivity in the brain and has been implicated in the control of conditions such as anxiety and sleep disorders. GABAergic neurons are thought to have a crucial role in emotional processing, sensory discrimination and this may impact motor skills.

Features of Autism tend to be over-excitability of the senses (visual, tactile and auditory) which can affect sensorimotor skills (balance, dexterity, stress, sleep and emotional processing. Since GABA is the main neurotransmitter for reducing over-excitability, it stands to reason to figure out how GABA is involved in ASC (Autism Spectrum Condition).

It turns out that people with Autism have much lower GABA levels in their brains than typical brains. This is due to structural and functional differences in the parts of the brain which produce GABA as well as a likelihood that the conversion process of Glutamate to GABA is impaired in people with ASC. Therefore, the sensory overloading in people with Autism is likely to be related to this reduced GABA and supplementing with GABA may be useful.

We supplied Coventry University with a selection of teas and tisanes with varying GABA and L-Theanine levels to use in a study with children with Autism and they have had very encouraging results.

Statistically, participants who drank Amber GABA Oolong tea daily had an overall improvement in manual dexterity, balance, reduction in stress, less sensory excitability and a reduced level on the Autism Spectrum Scale. This is compared with a placebo tisane that actually had some GABA content and therefore may actually have even better results compared with drinking no tea or tisanes at all.

This is a small feasibility study so it is far from conclusive but certainly warrants larger studies. A sensible conclusion for anyone with Autism or who have children with Autism is that it is worth trying to supplement with a few cups of GABA tea every day - it cannot be harmful so give it a try!

ABOUT AMBER GABA OOLONG
Normal Oolong tea contains around 10-30mg of GABA per 100g. For a tea to qualify as GABA tea it must contain at 150mg of GABA per 100g. Our Amber GABA has been tested to have over 200mg. The farmers achieve this by alternating the leaves between air and a vacuum environment during the oxidation phase. This is done over a matter of hours and naturally increases the GABA levels in the tea leaves.

amber heard's parents "didn't know how to process" things when she told them she was bisexual.

the 32-year-old actress identifies as bisexual and has said that telling her parents she was in a relationship with a woman for the first time wasn't easy, because of their "religious" background.

she said: "i am from austin, texas. my dad is out of central casting texan. good southern man, and i was raised in a religious home. and being an outspoken lesbian, atheist, vegetarian, i remember when i told them about my relationship, that i was in love with this woman, and at the beginning of that it was just tears, tears.‚Äù

but the 'aquaman' star says that while her parents didn't understand her sexuality at first, their "attitudes and hearts" changed over time.

speaking during a panel at sxsw, she added that five years later, she was getting an award and had asked her parents to drive out to dallas.

upon collecting her award, she said she could ‚Äúsee them sitting front and center and here i am getting this 'gay' award... my parents in five years, look at the journey. attitudes and hearts can change."

She said: "I am from Austin, Texas. My dad is out of central casting Texan. Good Southern man, and I was raised in a religious home. But the 'Aquaman' star says that while her parents didn't understand her sexuality at first, their "attitudes and hearts" changed over time.

Speaking during a panel at SXSW, she added that five years later, she was getting an award and had asked her parents to drive out to Dallas.

snippet.title: johnny depp lawsuit 'freaking out' warner bros. over potential harm to 'harry potter' franchise
snippet.description:
warner bros. is ‚Äúfreaking out‚Äù over its hit harry potter movie franchise‚Äôs connection to johnny depp after amber heard‚Äòs new court documents described in painstaking detail how he allegedly beat, choked and tormented her during their relationship, sources told the post on friday. 
depp ‚Äî who denies abusing heard ‚Äî is slated to star in ‚Äúfantastic beasts 3,‚Äù the next installment of j.k.rowling‚Äòs harry potter movies. the script has been completed, although filming, which was due to start this summer, has been delayed to the fall of next year. 
‚Äúexecutives at warner bros. are wondering how to deal with the backlash of the depp matter on the harry potter franchise,‚Äù a source said. ‚Äúhigh-level female execs at the studio are extremely worried about working with depp and the message it sends to the public, especially after the recent sordid departure of ceo kevin tsujihara,‚Äù who last month announced he was leaving amid a casting couch scandal. 
elon musk subpoenaed in johnny depp lawsuit against amber heard 
‚Äúthis is yet another blow to the morale of female employees at the studio,‚Äù the source said. ‚Äúif warner bros. continues to stick by depp, it would reveal a lot about the values the company holds.‚Äù 
while reps at warner bros. didn‚Äôt respond to multiple requests for comment from the post, insiders said executives are unsure how to proceed, since author j.k. rowling came out strongly in support of depp‚Äôs casting in a previous potter flick in 2017 after his marriage to heard crumbled. 
video
‚Äúmany at warner bros. wish that rowling hadn‚Äôt come out so strongly behind depp, because having made her opinion so public boxes them into a corner,‚Äù a source said. 
rowling broke her silence on the controversy surrounding depp‚Äôs casting as the villain grindelwald when she wrote on her website in december 2017, ‚Äúwhen johnny depp was cast as grindelwald, i thought he‚Äôd be wonderful in the role. however, around the time of filming his cameo in the first movie, stories had appeared in the press that deeply concerned me and everyone most closely involved in the franchise. 
johnny depp sues amber heard for $50 million, says she cheated on him with elon musk 
‚Äúharry potter fans had legitimate questions and concerns about our choice to continue with johnny depp in the role. as david yates, long-time potter director, has already said, we naturally considered the possibility of recasting. i understand why some have been confused and angry about why that didn‚Äôt happen.‚Äù 
rowling added that while ‚Äúthe huge, mutually supportive community that has grown up around harry potter is one of the greatest joys of my life,‚Äù she found it ‚Äúdifficult, frustrating and at times painful‚Äù to remain silent on the depp issue. 
referring to depp and heard‚Äôs divorce agreement, she added, ‚Äúhowever, the agreements that have been put in place to protect the privacy of two people, both of whom have expressed a desire to get on with their lives, must be respected. based on our understanding

Amber Heard‚Äòs billionaire ex-boyfriend Elon Musk is now being dragged into Johnny Depp‚Äòs $50 million defamation case against the actress. 
Depp‚Äôs legal team say they plan to drag Musk to court in Depp and Heard‚Äôs legal battle over her allegations of domestic violence, which he insists is a ‚Äúhoax.‚Äù 
‚ÄúWe have now issued subpoenas to Amber Heard, her hoax assisting friends, Elon Musk and other witnesses to explain the avalanche of video, audio, photographic and testimonial evidence with which we intend to confront them,‚Äù Depp‚Äôs attorney told Page Six in a statement on Friday. 
But a source close to the situation countered, ‚ÄúAs of now, Elon has not received anything.‚Äù 
Heard wrote an op-ed in the Washington Post about her experience as a victim of domestic violence, without mentioning Depp, who denies abusing her. 
But in March the ‚ÄúFantastic Beasts‚Äù actor filed a $50 million defamation suit against her claiming it was insinuated in the piece that he was the perpetrator. Depp‚Äôs legal team claimed in the lawsuit that the domestic violence claims against the actor were a ‚Äúhoax‚Äù to further Heard‚Äôs career. 
Depp‚Äôs lawsuit also accused Heard of having an affair with Tesla founder Musk while they were still married, which Musk has denied. 
Heard and Musk were first spotted together in July 2016 at a Miami Beach hotel around two months after the ‚ÄúAquaman‚Äù star filed for divorce from Depp. 
At the time a source insisted, ‚ÄúShe has been friends with Elon for four years.‚Äù 
In August 2016, it was revealed the Tesla co-founder had been trying to meet Heard for years. 
Musk, 47, and Heard, 32, were finally photographed together in Australia holding hands for the first time in April 2017. 
The couple split up a few months later in August but reunited in November and continued to rekindle their romance into 2018. Just one month later, they called it quits for good. 
In a new court filing, Heard said Depp would ‚Äúbecome a totally different person, often delusional and violent‚Äù when he was using drugs. 
‚ÄúWe called that version of Johnny, ‚Äòthe Monster,'‚Äù Heard said. 
‚ÄúThe root of Johnny‚Äôs violence against Amber, and now his defamation lawsuit against Amber, is his fixation, his jealousy and obsessive control and his need to exert ownership over her body,‚Äù a source close to the ex-couple told Page Six. 
‚ÄúIt is clear from Amber‚Äôs declaration that Johnny thought she was f**king Billy Bob Thornton, James Franco. Johnny‚Äôs lawsuit accuses her of cheating with Elon Musk, so now Depp wants to drag Elon into court.‚Äù 
Heard has never been linked with Thornton nor Franco, and Musk insists their relationship didn‚Äôt start until after her split with Depp. 
This story originally appeared in the New York Post.

snippet.title: moonchild: npr music tiny desk concert
snippet.description:
watch moonchild play "money", "the other side" and "the list" at the tiny desk.

more from npr music: 
tiny desk concerts: https://www.npr.org/tinydesk
twitter: https://twitter.com/nprmusic
instagram: https://www.instagram.com/nprmusic


dec. 16, 2019 | bobby carter -- many bands make considerable adjustments to their playing style in order for their sound to properly fill the tiny desk space. la-based trio moonchild, along with three background singers and a drummer, arrived promptly for their load-in time, unpacked their gear and were ready to go within minutes. aside from being especially efficient, their natural musical instincts made for a custom fit in our corner.

amber navran, max bryk and andris mattson joined forces in 2012 at the university of southern california and their debut album, be free soon followed. this year, they released their fourth album, little ghost, intricately meshing jazz, r&b and hip-hop sounds under amber's subtle vocal feats.

for their set, they pulled out all the stops: flutes, flugelhorns, saxophones, keyboards, ukuleles and some the best harmonies i've heard in recent memory. from the moment amber walked into the building and throughout the performance, she wore a smile on her face and expressed sincere gratitude for the tiny desk platform. she took advantage of the moment and amplified a cause near and dear to her heart. she asked us to "spend our privilege" and do more in the fight for people of color in the united states. they closed with a jam from 2017's voyager.

set list
"money"
"the other side"
"the list"

musicians
amber navran: vocals, saxophone, flute; andris mattson: keys, guitar, flugelhorn; max bryk: keys, saxophone, flute; erin bentlage: vocals, ukulele; efa etoroma jr.: drums; michael mayo: vocals; micah robinson: vocals

credits
producers: bobby carter, abby o'neill, morgan noelle smith; creative director: bob boilen; audio engineers: josh rogosin, alex drewenskus; videographers: morgan noelle smith, maia stern, kara frame, jack corbett; production assistant: zoe jones; executive producer: lauren onkey; vp, programming: anya grundmann; photo: catie dull/npr

Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/nprmusic


Dec. 16, 2019 | Bobby Carter -- Many bands make considerable adjustments to their playing style in order for their sound to properly fill the Tiny Desk space. LA-based trio Moonchild, along with three background singers and a drummer, arrived promptly for their load-in time, unpacked their gear and were ready to go within minutes. Aside from being especially efficient, their natural musical instincts made for a custom fit in our corner.

Amber Navran, Max Bryk and Andris Mattson joined forces in 2012 at the University of Southern California and their debut album, Be Free soon followed. This year, they released their fourth album, Little Ghost, intricately meshing jazz, R&B and hip-hop sounds under Amber's subtle vocal feats.

For their set, they pulled out all the stops: flutes, flugelhorns, saxophones, keyboards, ukuleles and some the best harmonies I've heard in recent memory. From the moment Amber walked into the building and throughout the performance, she wore a smile on her face and expressed sincere gratitude for the Tiny Desk platform. She took advantage of the moment and amplified a cause near and dear to her heart. She asked us to "spend our privilege" and do more in the fight for people of color in the United States. They closed with a jam from 2017's Voyager.

SET LIST
"Money"
"The Other Side"
"The List"

MUSICIANS
Amber Navran: vocals, saxophone, flute; Andris Mattson: keys, guitar, flugelhorn; Max Bryk: keys, saxophone, flute; Erin Bentlage: vocals, ukulele; Efa Etoroma Jr.: drums; Michael Mayo: vocals; Micah Robinson: vocals

CREDITS

amber laura heard (born april 22, 1986) is an american actress and model. born and raised in texas, heard made her film debut in a minor supporting role in the sports drama friday night lights (2004), followed by a series of other small roles in television and film. her first leading role was in the horror film all the boys love mandy lane (2006), but it was not released in the united states until 2013 due to distribution problems. her second major role came in the short-running the cw television series hidden palms (2007).

heard's breakthrough came in 2008 with roles in the action film never back down and in the stoner comedy pineapple express, which were both box office successes. the same year, she received the breakthrough award at young hollywood awards. heard continued her career with roles in films such as the informers (2008), the stepfather (2009), zombieland (2009), and the joneses (2009). in 2011, she played the female lead opposite nicolas cage in drive angry, and opposite johnny depp in the rum diary; neither were critically nor commercially successful. after several unsuccessful films, heard appeared in the box office successes 3 days to kill (2014), magic mike xxl (2015) and the danish girl (2015). she also starred in the indie film the adderall diaries (2015), the television musical drama one more time (2015), and the martin amis adaptation london fields (2018). the latter was due to be released in 2015 but became the subject of a series of a lawsuit between its director, heard, and the film's production company over disagreements in its editing and other issues. the film was finally released in 2018 and was both a critical and commercial flop.

in 2017, heard acted as part of an ensemble cast in the indie film i do...until i don't (2017) and made an appearance as mera in the superhero film justice league (2017). she reprised the latter role opposite jason momoa in aquaman (2018), which became the most profitable dc extended universe film up to that point, and the fifth highest-grossing film of 2018.[4] the same year, heard was also named a global spokesperson for the cosmetics giant l'or√©al paris. in 2019, she appeared in supporting roles in the independent films her smell and gully.

in addition to her acting career, heard engages in activism for causes such as lgbtq rights and domestic and sexual violence awareness. she is an american civil liberties union (aclu) ambassador and has been named a human rights champion for the stand up for human rights campaign by the office of the united nations high commissioner for human rights. from 2015 to 2017, heard was married to her the rum diary co-star johnny depp. their divorce drew significant media attention, as she alleged that he was physically and verbally abusive towards her throughout most of their relationship.

snippet.localized.title: HOT: Amber Heard (Mera Aquaman) Hot Compilation 720p
snippet.localized.description:
Amber Laura Heard (born April 22, 1986) is an American actress and model. Born and raised in Texas, Heard made her film debut in a minor supporting role in the sports drama Friday Night Lights (2004), followed by a series of other small roles in television and film. Her first leading role was in the horror film All the Boys Love Mandy Lane (2006), but it was not released in the United States until 2013 due to distribution problems. Her second major role came in the short-running The CW television series Hidden Palms (2007).

Heard's breakthrough came in 2008 with roles in the action film Never Back Down and in the stoner comedy Pineapple Express, which were both box office successes. The same year, she received the Breakthrough Award at Young Hollywood Awards. Heard continued her career with roles in films such as The Informers (2008), The Stepfather (2009), Zombieland (2009), and The Joneses (2009). In 2011, she played the female lead opposite Nicolas Cage in Drive Angry, and opposite Johnny Depp in The Rum Diary; neither were critically nor commercially successful. After several unsuccessful films, Heard appeared in the box office successes 3 Days to Kill (2014), Magic Mike XXL (2015) and The Danish Girl (2015). She also starred in the indie film The Adderall Diaries (2015), the television musical drama One More Time (2015), and the Martin Amis adaptation London Fields (2018). The latter was due to be released in 2015 but became the subject of a series of a lawsuit between its director, Heard, and the film's production company over disagreements in its editing and other issues. The film was finally released in 2018 and was both a critical and commercial flop.

In 2017, Heard acted as part of an ensemble cast in the indie film I Do...Until I Don't (2017) and made an appearance as Mera in the superhero film Justice League (2017). She reprised the latter role opposite Jason Momoa in Aquaman (2018), which became the most profitable DC Extended Universe film up to that point, and the fifth highest-grossing film of 2018.[4] The same year, Heard was also named a global spokesperson for the cosmetics giant L'Or√©al Paris. In 2019, she appeared in supporting roles in the independent films Her Smell and Gully.

In addition to her acting career, Heard engages in activism for causes such as LGBTQ rights and domestic and sexual violence awareness. She is an American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) ambassador and has been named a Human Rights Champion for the Stand Up for Human Rights campaign by the Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights. From 2015 to 2017, Heard was married to her The Rum Diary co-star Johnny Depp. Their divorce drew significant media attention, as she alleged that he was physically and verbally abusive towards her throughout most of their relationship.

snippet.title: amber heard asks judge to dismiss johnny depp's $50m defamation lawsuit
snippet.description:
johnny depp, left, and amber heard arrive for the european premiere of their film, "the rum diary," in london. (ap photo/joel ryan, file) 
actress amber heard asked a judge thursday to dismiss a $50 million defamation lawsuit her ex-husband johnny depp filed over an op-ed about domestic violence she wrote in the washington post. 
in the motion filed in the circuit court of fairfax, virginia, heard reiterates her allegations that depp abused her before and during their marriage and includes exhibits such as photos of her with bruises on her face and scars on her arms, images of damage she says depp did to their home, screenshots of text messages describing the incidents at the time, and excerpts of her divorce deposition describing domestic abuse. 
prosecutors decline to charge michael avenatti on abuse claim: report 
"johnny depp physically and verbally abused amber heard," her attorney eric george said in a statement. "since their divorce, mr. depp has continued to publically harass ms. heard, and attempted to gaslight the world by denying his abuse. it is long past time for mr. depp's despicable conduct to end." 
depp's lawsuit, filed last month, called the ongoing allegations of domestic abuse "categorically and demonstrably false." 
"they were part of an elaborate hoax to generate positive publicity for ms. heard and advance her career," the lawsuit states, claiming that "she is the perpetrator." 
depp's attorney, adam waldman, said he was reviewing the new filing. he said previously that he and depp looked forward to providing evidence that would clear depp's name. 
the post piece by heard, published in december, does not mention depp by name or describe any incidents, but it discusses the societal plight of those who speak up about domestic abuse. 
"i spoke up against sexual violence ‚Äî and faced our culture's wrath," the 32-year-old actress wrote, adding that she felt as though she was "on trial in the court of public opinion." 
but depp's lawsuit says it was clear heard was talking about him, and that it worsened the damage the allegations had already done to his career. 
the lawsuit states depp, 55, has suffered financial losses because of the accusations, including being dropped from his role as capt. jack sparrow in the "pirates of the caribbean" films. 
heard's lawyers also argued that the lawsuit should be moved to los angeles because that's where the relevant events took place. 
heard first accused depp of domestic violence in may 2016, the year after they were married. they were divorced in 2017.

the actress, whose credits include "aquaman" and "justice league," met depp on the set of their 2011 film "the rum diary."
snippet.localized.title: Amber Heard asks judge to dismiss Johnny Depp's $50M defamation lawsuit
snippet.localized.description:
Johnny Depp, left, and Amber Heard arrive for the European premiere of their film, "The Rum Diary," in London. (AP Photo/Joel Ryan, File) 
Actress Amber Heard asked a judge Thursday to dismiss a $50 million defamation lawsuit her ex-husband Johnny Depp filed over an op-ed about domestic violence she wrote in The Washington Post. 
In the motion filed in the Circuit Court of Fairfax, Virginia, Heard reiterates her allegations that Depp abused her before and during their marriage and includes exhibits such as photos of her with bruises on her face and scars on her arms, images of damage she says Depp did to their home, screenshots of text messages describing the incidents at the time, and excerpts of her divorce deposition describing domestic abuse. 
PROSECUTORS DECLINE TO CHARGE MICHAEL AVENATTI ON ABUSE CLAIM: REPORT 
"Johnny Depp physically and verbally abused Amber Heard," her attorney Eric George said in a statement. "Since their divorce, Mr. Depp has continued to publically harass Ms. Heard, and attempted to gaslight the world by denying his abuse. It is long past time for Mr. Depp's despicable conduct to end." 
Depp's lawsuit, filed last month, called the ongoing allegations of domestic abuse "categorically and demonstrably false." 
"They were part of an elaborate hoax to generate positive publicity for Ms. Heard and advance her career," the lawsuit states, claiming that "she is the perpetrator." 
Depp's attorney, Adam Waldman, said he was reviewing the new filing. He said previously that he and Depp looked forward to providing evidence that would clear Depp's name. 
The Post piece by Heard, published in December, does not mention Depp by name or describe any incidents, but it discusses the societal plight of those who speak up about domestic abuse. 
"I spoke up against sexual violence ‚Äî and faced our culture's wrath," the 32-year-old actress wrote, adding that she felt as though she was "on trial in the court of public opinion." 
But Depp's lawsuit says it was clear Heard was talking about him, and that it worsened the damage the allegations had already done to his career. 
The lawsuit states Depp, 55, has suffered financial losses because of the accusations, including being dropped from his role as Capt. Jack Sparrow in the "Pirates of the Caribbean" films. 
Heard's lawyers also argued that the lawsuit should be moved to Los Angeles because that's where the relevant events took place. 
Heard first accused Depp of domestic violence in May 2016, the year after they were married. They were divorced in 2017.

snippet.title: press group warns against libel suit by johnny depp against amber heard
snippet.description:
(8 nov 2019) press group warns against libel suit by johnny depp against amber heard
free press advocates in virginia are concerned that a libel lawsuit between two hollywood stars could set a bad precedent.
the virginia press association asked friday (8 nov. 2019) to intervene in a $50 million (usd) lawsuit filed by johnny depp against his ex-wife, actress amber heard. depp says he was defamed by an article heard wrote in the washington post. she never identified depp by name but referred to herself as a "public figure representing domestic abuse."
the press association argued friday in fairfax county circuit court that the case could set a bad precedent for cases involving "defamation by implication."
a judge, though, barred the press association from filing any briefs outlining its position. he said his job was to apply the law as it exists without considering the association's policy concerns.

snippet.localized.title: Press group warns against libel suit by Johnny Depp against Amber Heard
snippet.localized.description:
(8 Nov 2019) PRESS GROUP WARNS AGAINST LIBEL SUIT BY JOHNNY DEPP AGAINST AMBER HEARD
Free press advocates in Virginia are concerned that a libel lawsuit between two Hollywood stars could set a bad precedent.
The Virginia Press Association asked Friday (8 NOV. 2019) to intervene in a $50 million (USD) lawsuit filed by Johnny Depp against his ex-wife, actress Amber Heard. Depp says he was defamed by an article Heard wrote in The Washington Post. She never identified Depp by name but referred to herself as a "public figure representing domestic abuse."
The press association argued Friday in Fairfax County Circuit Court that the case could set a bad precedent for cases involving "defamation by implication."
A judge, though, barred the press association from filing any briefs outlining its position. He said his job was to apply the law as it exists without considering the association's policy concerns.

They even issued a joint statement during the time of their divorce, saying, "Our relationship was intensely passionate and at times volatile, but always bound by love. snippet.title: camila cabello, amber heard, helen mirren, eva longoria walk in l'oreal show at paris fashion week
snippet.description:
(28 sep 2019) cabello, heard, mirren, longoria walk in l'oreal show at paris fashion week
cabila cabello, amber heard, helen mirren and eva longoria were among the stars walking the runway at l'oreal paris' third annual fashion show during paris fashion week. 
the show dubbed "le d√©fil√©" was held in the courtyard of the monnaie de paris on saturday afternoon (28 september 2019), featuring a diverse selection of models and spokespeople. 
heard and cabello, both brand ambassadors, made their first-ever appearances for the house. longoria carried her baby son, santiago, onto the runway for the grand finale. mirren and andie macdowell proved that beauty knows no age. 
the 32-model lineup also included doutzen kroes, soo joo park, and aishwarya rai. stars such as naomi campbell and olga kurylenko watched from the front row, in the company of the brand's first-ever female president, delphine viguier-hovasse.
fashions were by emerging labels as well as renowned brands including balmain, dries van noten, elie saab, karl lagerfeld and more. a 40-musician orchestra accompanied the show.

Cabila Cabello, Amber Heard, Helen Mirren and Eva Longoria were among the stars walking the runway at L'Oreal Paris' third annual fashion show during Paris Fashion Week. 
The show dubbed "Le D√©fil√©" was held in the courtyard of the Monnaie de Paris on Saturday afternoon (28 SEPTEMBER 2019), featuring a diverse selection of models and spokespeople. 
Heard and Cabello, both brand ambassadors, made their first-ever appearances for the house. Longoria carried her baby son, Santiago, onto the runway for the grand finale. Mirren and Andie MacDowell proved that beauty knows no age.

Amber Heard and Johny Depp | Career Highlights of Heard.

Amber Heard acted in Aquaman, London Fields, Justice League, and others. She was married to Johnny Depp between 2015 and 2017. Amber Heard was born in Austin, Texas, in 1986. When she was 17, she dropped out of high school and moved to Los Angeles to pursue an acting and modeling career. Her first movie role was in the 2004 sports drama "friday night lights," which starred billy bob thornton. (It later became a TV show.). Amber Heard appeared in the Academy Award-nominated film, North Country (2005), in which she played Charlize Theron's character in flashbacks. Her major acting breakthrough came when she was cast as the title character, a shy outsider turned teen mass-murderer, in All the Boys Love Mandy Lane (2006). Heard's breakthrough came in 2008 with roles in Never Back Down and Pineapple Express. She received the Breakthrough Award at Young Hollywood Awards. Heard filed for divorce against Depp on May 23, 2016 and four days later requested a temporary domestic violence restraining order against him, which a judge granted.
